With no major problems during my stay here (apart from a horrible mosquito bite and little traffic accident), it comes as no surprise that Kashmir is one of India’s favourite spots for tourists. The area (the state) extends over a large area east of Amritsar in the Himalayas in North India, avoiding staying south of the Line of Control, where Pakistan was born, and claiming the Jammu and rest of the state to be its own.

The valley is very beautiful and it is not for nothing that tourism is steadily falling. In the Chandigarh area there are good roads and infrastructure despite the slow traffic, you can safely and easily hire a car to take you around.

Even the road to Kashmir itself is not for the faint of heart. The same way as to Dharamsala and many other spots in the Himalyas but more on the east side without the high buildings next to the road, it winds through mountains with strong bends, shocks badly and fine sandy patches
